<DOC><DOCNO> AP880527-0252 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-27-88 2038EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-FirefighterDeaths     05-27 0326</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Firefighter Deaths,0336</SECOND><HEAD>Firefighter Fatalities Up; Heart Attack Still Number One Killer</HEAD><DATELINE>QUINCY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The number of firefighters who died in theline of duty hit a seven-year high last year, with heart attacksagain claiming the most lives, a national safety organizationreported Friday.   The National Fire Protection Association reported 124 fatalitiesin 1987, a 9.7 percent increase over the previous year and the mostsince 1981, when 134 firefighters died.   There were 72 volunteers and 52 career firefighters among the1987 fatalities, according to the non-profit group that claims morethan 44,000 members nationwide.   Overall, heart attacks continued to be the number one killer,striking down 56 firefighters, the group said.   Other major causes of fatalities included internal trauma, 28deaths; asphyxiation, 13 deaths; and crushing, 12 deaths.   Of the heart attack victims, 14 had prior heart problems; 10 hadsevere heart disease; two suffered from hypertension and one wasfatigued prior to the attack. Heart attack has been the major causeof firefighter fatalities since the study began 11 years ago, thegroup said.   While the number of fatal heart attacks among firefighters over40 years old was down 16 percent from the previous year, thenumbers were slightly higher among younger firefighters. There werefive fatal heart attack victims under 35 years old, including twounder 20.   Fifty-three firefighters were killed while fighting fires, with24 dying from heart attacks, 10 from internal trauma, eight fromsmoke inhalation, six from being crushed, two from burns, two fromgunshot wounds and one from electrocution.   Thirty-five firefighters were killed while responding to orreturning from an alarm.   For the first time since the association began issuing thereport, the largest proportion of deaths in the line of dutyoccurred during wildland fires. Seventeen firefighters were killedbattling such blazes, while five died responding to or returningfrom wildland fires.   Fires of suspicious origins accounted for 23 deaths, accordingto the statistics.</TEXT></DOC>